  "prompt": "Though people tell me I am pretty, why do I sometimes feel not pretty or I don't like what I see in the mirror?",
  "response": "It's completely normal to have conflicting feelings about your appearance, even when others perceive you as pretty. Here are a few reasons why you might feel this way:\n\n1. **Self-Perception vs. External Validation**: Our self-image often differs from how others see us. You might focus on perceived flaws or imperfections that others do not notice or that they admire.\n\n2. **Cultural Standards and Media Influence**: Societal beauty standards are often unrealistic and can impact how we view ourselves. Exposure to idealized images in media can lead you to feel inadequate or unpretty.\n\n3. **Mood and Mental Health**: Your emotional state can affect how you perceive yourself. Stress, anxiety, and depression can amplify negative self-image.\n\n4. **Comparison with Others**: Social comparison can lead to feelings of inadequacy, especially if you find yourself comparing your appearance to those of people you admire.\n\n5. **Natural Fluctuations**: It's common for self-esteem to fluctuate based on a variety of factors - how you feel that day, what you are wearing, or even the lighting in the room.\n\n6. **Inner Dialogue**: How you talk to yourself matters. Negative self-talk or criticism can shape your self-perception.\n\nIf you're struggling with these feelings, it may help to explore them with a friend, family member, or a mental health professional. Developing self-compassion and reducing negative self-talk can significantly improve your self-image over time.",
